        <marginalia hand="Italian">
            <language ident="LA">
                <position place="full_page" book_orientation="0">
                    <marginalia_text>Epitaphium Sturni; cognomento Pisitatoris. <!--JG: Who could author be, assuming that it wasn't Harvey himself who wrote this? Maffeo Vegio wrote a 'Epitaphium Parrochini sturni, but the text is completely different-->
                        Sturnus, ego, haud ulli volucrum Virtute secundus, <!--JG: Aeneis, bk II, 441: 'Turnus ego, haud ulli veterum virtute secundus...' -->
                    Conditus h&icirc;c Domini munere, vera cano.
                    Ridiculus me Mus (dictu quam turpe?) necauit,
                    Compuleram toties quem dare terga fuga[e].
                    Ast Somni, Noctisq[ue] dolis decepit opaca[e];
                    Quorum etiam technis Regna superba ruunt.
                    Discite Aues sapere, et nulla illaguiarier Arte:
                    Prudenti Tumulus sufficit vnus Aui.
                    Credulitatem odi: nocuit sperare columbis:
                    Sturnus amat vigiles: cauta, Pronoia, Dea est.
                    Quisquis ades, Sturni miseratus Fata, memento
                    Vitam ex morte mea consolidare tuam.
                    
                    Gabriel Haruejus. 1580.</marginalia_text>
                    <person name="Gabriel Harvey"/>
                </position>
            </language>
            <translation>A eulogy of the starling; with the nickname 'Pisitator'. <!--JG: From the verb 'pisitare', the cry of a starling-->
                I, a starling, second to none of the birds in virtue, lay buried here through the service of the Lord, and I sing the truth. 
                A ridiculous mouse killed me (embarrassing enough?), that I had often forced to flee. But he deceived [me] by tricks of sleep and dark night,
                the cunning tricks which even collapse proud kingdoms. Learn to think, birds, and be ensared by no craftiness: one tomb suffices for a prudent bird. I hate trustfulness: it is damaging to pigeons to be hopeful. 
                A starling loves those who are watchful: cautious providence is his goddess. Whoever you are here, feel pity for the fate of the starling, and then remember to consolidate your life through my death. 
                Gabriel Harvey, 1580. 
            </translation> <!--JG: Many thanks to Prof Arnoud Visser for helping me with the translation-->
        </marginalia>
        
